                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">No. 853</seg>
                </opener>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>Yugoslav Deputy Minister of Foreign Trade <persName corresp="#p_VV1">Vladimir
                        Velebit</persName> visited Washington at the end of 1950 to obtain economic
                    assistance from the World Bank. At a dinner given by <persName corresp="#p_JRP1"
                        >Robert P. Joyce</persName> of the Policy Planning Staff on November 22,
                    United States officials raised with <persName corresp="#p_VV1"
                        >Velebit</persName> the possibility of political support and military
                    assistance to Yugoslavia. Without committing his government, <persName
                        corresp="#p_VV1">Velebit</persName> returned to Belgrade for consultations.
                    By December 29 <persName corresp="#p_VV1">Velebit</persName> was back in
                    Washington with a detailed shopping list of military equipment and supplies
                    needed on an emergency basis by Yugoslavia. Further discussions with <persName
                        corresp="#p_JRP1">Joyce</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_RGF1">G.
                        Frederick</persName>
                    <persName corresp="#p_RGF1">Reinhardt</persName>, Director of the Office of
                    Eastern European Affairs, on February 3, led to an agreement on assistance.
                    Documentation on these conversations is in file 768.5. For Congressional
                    testimony by General <persName corresp="#p_WGH1">George H. Olmsted</persName>,
                    Office of Military Assistance, Department of Defense, on the nature of the
                    shipments to Yugoslavia, see U.S. House of Representatives, Committee on Foreign
                    Affairs, <hi rend="italic">Selected Executive Session Hearings of the Committee,
                        1951–56</hi>, volume XV, European Problems (Washington, 1980), pages 140
                    ff.</p>
            </div>
